'''Solomon''', also '''Salomon''' ({{lang-hu|Salamon}}; 1053&nbsp;<U+2013> 1087) was [[King of Hungary]] from 1063. Being the elder son of [[Andrew I of Hungary]], he was crowned king in his father's lifetime in 1057 or 1058. However, he was forced to flee from Hungary after his uncle, [[B<U+00E9>la I of Hungary|B<U+00E9>la]] dethroned his father in 1060. Assisted by German troops, Solomon returned and was again crowned king in 1063. On this occasion he married [[Judith of Swabia|Judith]], who was a daughter of the late [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor]]. In the following year he reached an agreement with his cousins, the three sons of the late B<U+00E9>la I. [[G<U+00E9>za I of Hungary|G<U+00E9>za]], [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus]] and [[Lampert of Hungary|Lampert]] acknowledged Solomon's rule, but in exchange received one-third of the kingdom as a separate [[Duchy (Kingdom of Hungary)|duchy]].

In the following years, Solomon and his cousins jointly fought against the [[Czechs]], the [[Cumans]] and other enemies of the kingdom. Their relationship deteriorated in the early 1070s and G<U+00E9>za rebelled against him. Solomon could only maintain his rule in a small zone along the western frontiers of Hungary after his defeat in the [[battle of Mogyor<U+00F3>d]] on 14 March 1074. He officially abdicated in 1081, but was arrested for conspiring against G<U+00E9>za's brother and successor, Ladislaus.

Solomon was set free during the canonization process of the first king of Hungary, [[Stephen I of Hungary|Stephen I]] in 1083. In an attempt to regain his crown, Solomon allied with the [[Pechenegs]], but King Ladislaus defeated their invading troops. According to a nearly contemporaneous source, Solomon died on a plundering raid in the [[Byzantine Empire]]. Later legends say that he survived and died as a saintly hermit in [[Pula]] (Croatia).

==Early life==
Solomon was a son of King [[Andrew I of Hungary]] and his wife, [[Anastasia of Kiev]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=69, 87}} His parents were married in about 1038.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=69}} He was born in 1053{{sfn|Makk|1994|p=77}} as his parents' second child and eldest son.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}

His father had him crowned king in 1057 or 1058.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}} Solomon's coronation was a fundamental condition of his engagement to [[Judith of Swabia|Judith]], a sister of [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]], [[King of Germany]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=31}} Their engagement put an end to the more than ten-year-long period of armed conflicts between Hungary and the [[Holy Roman Empire]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=60}}{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=35}} However, Solomon's coronation provoked his uncle, [[B<U+00E9>la I of Hungary|B<U+00E9>la]], who had until that time held a strong claim to succeed his brother Andrew according to the traditional principle of [[seniority]].{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=31}}{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=35}} B<U+00E9>la had, since around 1048, administered the so-called ''[[Duchy (Kingdom of Hungary)|ducatus]]'' or duchy, which encompassed one-third of the kingdom.{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=30-31}}
[[File:Andrew I of Hungary on his death bed (crop).jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=B<U+00E9>la chooses the sword | The scene at [[Tiszav<U+00E1>rkony]] depicted in the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'': the paralyzed King [[Andrew I of Hungary|Andrew]] forces Duke B<U+00E9>la to choose between the crown and the sword]]
[[File:B<U+00E9>la elnyeri a koron<U+00E1>t .jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=B<U+00E9>la's coronation | Solomon is deprived of the crown, and his uncle, [[B<U+00E9>la I of Hungary|B<U+00E9>la]] is crowned king (from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'')]]
{{Quote|''Because carnal love and ties of blood are wont to prove a hindrance to truthfulness, in King Andreas love for his son overcame justice, so that he broke the treaty of his promise, which in kings should not be; in the twelfth year of his reign, when he was worn out with age, he caused his son Salomon, who was still a child of five years, to be [[Anointing#Christian monarchy|anointed]] and crowned king over all Hungary. He pretended that he did this to prevent injury to his kingdom, for the [[Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor]] would not have given his daughter to his son Salomon unless he had crowned him. When therefore they sang at Salomon's coronation: "[[Book of Genesis|Be lord over thy brethren]]," and it was told to Duke Bela by an interpreter that the infant Salomon had been made king over him, he was greatly angered.''|''[[Illuminated Chronicle|The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle]]''<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 64.91), p. 115.</ref>}}

According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', in order to secure Solomon's succession, his father arranged a meeting with Duke B<U+00E9>la at the royal manor in [[Tiszav<U+00E1>rkony]].{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=31}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=60}} The king proposed that his brother choose between a crown and a sword (which were the symbols of royal and ducal power, respectively), but had previously commanded his men to murder the duke if B<U+00E9>la picked the crown.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=31}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=60}}

The duke, whom a courtier had informed of the king's plan, chose the crown, then left Hungary after the meeting.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=31}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=60}} He sought the assistance of Duke [[Boleslaus the Bold]] of Poland and returned with Polish reinforcements.{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}}{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=35}} B<U+00E9>la emerged the victor in the ensuing civil war, during which Solomon's father was mortally injured in a battle.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=35}} Solomon and his mother fled to the Holy Roman Empire and settled in [[Melk]] in [[Margraviate of Austria|Austria]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=35}}{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=61}}

B<U+00E9>la was crowned king on 6 December 1060,{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}} but the young German king's advisors, who were staunch supporters of Solomon (the fianc<U+00E9> of their monarch's sister), refused to conclude a peace treaty with him.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=53}} In the summer of 1063, the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|assembly of the German princes]] decided to invade Hungary in order to restore Solomon.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=78}} Solomon's uncle died in an accident on 11 September, before the imperial army arrived.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|pp=80-81}} His three sons{{mdash}}[[G<U+00E9>za I of Hungary|G<U+00E9>za]], [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus]] and [[Lampert of Hungary|Lampert]]{{mdash}}left for Poland.{{sfn|Kontler|1999|p=61}}

==Reign==
[[File:Chronicon Pictum P069 IV Henrik <U+00E9>s Salamon.JPG|thumb |right |190px |alt=Solomon returns to Hungary | Solomon, assisted by [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV of Germany]], returns to Hungary (from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'')]]
Accompanied back to Hungary by German troops, Solomon entered [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] without resistance.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}} He was ceremoniously "crowned king with the consent and acclamation of all Hungary"<ref name="Chronicon_69.97_117">''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 69.97), p. 117.</ref> in September 1063, according to the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}} The same source adds that the German monarch "seated" Solomon "upon his father's throne",<ref name="Chronicon_69.97_117"/> but did not require him to take an oath of fealty.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}}{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}} Solomon's marriage with Henry IV's sister, Judith{{mdash}}who was six year older than her future husband{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}}{{mdash}}also took place on this occasion.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=53}} Judith, along with the Queen Mother Anastasia, became one of her young husband's principal advisors.{{sfn|Makk|1994|p=77}}

Solomon's three cousins{{mdash}}G<U+00E9>za and his brothers{{mdash}}returned after the German troops had been withdrawn from Hungary.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}} They arrived with Polish reinforcements and Solomon sought refuge in the fortress of [[Mosonmagyar<U+00F3>v<U+00E1>r|Moson]] at the western border of his kingdom.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=88}} The Hungarian prelates began to mediate between them in order to avoid a new civil war.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}}

Solomon and his cousins eventually reached an agreement, which was signed in [[Gy<U+0151>r]] on 20 January 1064.{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=26}} G<U+00E9>za and his brothers acknowledged Solomon as lawful king, and Solomon granted them their father's one-time ''ducatus''.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=89}} In token of their reconciliation, Duke G<U+00E9>za put a crown on Solomon's head in the cathedral of [[P<U+00E9>cs]] on [[Easter Sunday]].{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=81}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=89}} Their relationship remained tense; when the cathedral burned down during the following night, they initially accused each other of [[arson]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=89}}

{{Quote|[Sudden] ''flames seized that church and the palaces and all nearby buildings, and they collapsed in one devastating conflagration. Everyone was gripped with fear at the shock of the roaring flames and the terrible shattering of the bells as they fell from the towers; and none knew where to turn. The King and the Duke were in an amazed stupor; terrified by the suspicion of foul work, each went his separate way. In the morning they were apprised through faithful messengers that in truth there had not been on either side any evil intention of treachery, but that the fire had been happening of chance. The King and the Duke came together again in the goodness of peace.''|''[[Illuminated Chronicle|The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle]]''<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 70.99), p. 118.</ref>}}

The king and his cousins closely cooperated in the period between 1064 and 1071.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=82}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=90}} Both Solomon and G<U+00E9>za were, in 1065 or 1066, present at the consecration of the [[Benedictine]] [[Zselicszentjakab Abbey]], established by [[Palatine (Kingdom of Hungary)|Palatine]] [[Otto Gy<U+0151>r|Otto of the Gy<U+0151>r clan]], a partisan of the king.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=90}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|pp=39, 44}} They invaded [[Bohemia]] together after the [[Czechs]] had plundered the region of [[Trencs<U+00E9>n]] (present-day Tren<U+010D><U+00ED>n, Slovakia) in 1067.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=82}}{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=89}} During the following year, nomadic tribes broke into [[Transylvania]] and plundered the regions, but Solomon and his cousins routed them at [[Kerl<U+00E9>s]] (present-day Chirale<U+015F>, Romania).{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=82}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=251}} The identification of the marauders is uncertain: the ''[[Annales Posonienses]]'' and Simon of K<U+00E9>za write of Pechenegs, the 14th-century Hungarian chronicles refer to Cumans, and a Russian chronicle mentions the Cumans and the [[Vlachs]].{{sfn|Spinei|2009|p=118}} 
[[File:Chronicon Pictum P78 Salamon <U+00E9>s G<U+00E9>za visz<U+00E1>lya.JPG|thumb |left |190px |alt=Solomon and Count Vid, G<U+00E9>za and the Byzantine envoys | Count Vid incites Solomon against Duke [[G<U+00E9>za I of Hungary|G<U+00E9>za]] who receives the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] envoys in the background (from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'')]]
[[File:Picta Sal.jpg|thumb |left |190px |alt=Solomon and G<U+00E9>za at Ni<U+0161>| Solomon and [[G<U+00E9>za I of Hungary|G<U+00E9>za]] receive "gifts" from the locals at [[Ni<U+0161>]] (from the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]'')]]
Pecheneg troops pillaged [[Syrmia]] (now in [[Serbia]]) in 1071.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=82}}{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=89}} As the king and the duke suspected that the soldiers of the [[Byzantine army|Byzantine]] garrison at [[Belgrade]] incited the marauders against Hungary, they decided to attack the fortress.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=82}} The Hungarian army crossed the river [[Sava]], although the Byzantines "blew [[Greek fire|sulphurous fires]] by means of machines"<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 74.104), p. 119.</ref> against their boats.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=252}} The Hungarians took Belgrade after a siege of three months.{{sfn|Stephenson|2000|p=141}} However, the Byzantine commander, Niketas, surrendered the fortress to Duke G<U+00E9>za instead of the king; he knew that Solomon "was a hard man and that in all things he listened to the vile counsels of Count Vid, who was detestable in the eyes both of God and men",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 77.109), p. 120.</ref> according to the ''Illuminated Chronicle''.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=83}}

Division of the war-booty caused a new conflict between Solomon and his cousin, because the king granted only a quarter of the booty to the duke, who claimed its third part.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|pp=83-84}} Thereafter the duke negotiated with the [[Byzantine Emperor]]'s envoys and set all the Byzantine captives free without the king's consent.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=91}} The conflict was further sharpened by Count Vid; the ''Illuminated Chronicle'' narrates how the count incited the young monarch against his cousins by saying that as "two sharp swords cannot be kept in the same [[scabbard]]", so the king and the duke "cannot reign together in the same kingdom".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 78.110), p. 121.</ref> {{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=84}}

The Byzantines reoccupied Belgrade in the next year.{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=90}} Solomon decided to invade the Byzantine Empire and ordered his cousins to accompany him.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=84}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=92}} Only G<U+00E9>za joined the king; his brother, Ladislaus, remained with half of their troops in the [[Ny<U+00ED>rs<U+00E9>g]].{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=84}}{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=92}} Solomon and G<U+00E9>za marched along the valley of the river [[Great Morava]] as far as [[Ni<U+0161>]].{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=90}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=252}} Here the locals made them "rich gifts of gold and silver and precious cloaks"<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 79.112), p. 121.</ref> and Solomon seized the arm of Saint [[Procopius of Scythopolis]].{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=90}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=252}} He donated the [[relic]] to the [[Eastern Orthodoxy|Orthodox]] monastery of [[Syrmium]] (present-day Sremska Mitrovica, [[Serbia]]).{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=90}}{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=252}}

After their return from the campaign, both Solomon and G<U+00E9>za began to make preparations for their inevitable conflict and were seeking assistance from abroad.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=93}} They concluded a truce, which was to last "from the feast of [[Martin of Tours|St Martin]] until the feast of [[Saint George|St George]]", from 11 November 1073 until 24 April 1074.{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=90}} However, Solomon chose to attack his cousin as soon as the German troops sent by his brother-in-law arrived in Hungary.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=93}} The royal army crossed the river Tisza and routed the troops of G<U+00E9>za, who had been abandoned by many of his nobles before the battle, at Kemej on 26 February 1074.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=93}}{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=86}}

A strong army soon arrived in Hungary, headed by G<U+00E9>za's brother-in-law, Duke [[Otto I of Olomouc]].{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=86}} In the decisive battle, which was [[Battle of Mogyor<U+00F3>d|fought at Mogyor<U+00F3>d]] on 14 March 1074, Solomon was defeated and forced to flee from the battlefield.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=86}}

==Abdication==
[[File:Orlai-salamon.jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=Solomon and his mother |''King Solomon is cursed by his mother'', a picture by [[Soma Orlai Petrich]]]]
[[File:SalamounUhry.jpg|thumb |right |190px |alt=Solomon in Henry IV's court |Solomon appeals to [[Henry IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Henry IV]] for help]]
After the battle of Mogyor<U+00F3>d, Duke G<U+00E9>za's soldiers pursued Solomon and his men "from dawn to dusk",<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 85.121), p. 124.</ref> but they managed to take refugee in Moson, where his mother and wife had been staying.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=94}} According to the ''Illuminated Chronicle'', the queen mother blamed her son for the defeat, which filled Solomon with so much anger that he wanted to "strike his mother in the face".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 87.123), p. 125.</ref> His wife held him back by catching his hand.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=94}}

Thereafter, Solomon preserved only Moson and the nearby [[Pressburg]] (Bratislava, Slovakia). Other parts of the kingdom accepted the rule of G<U+00E9>za, who had been proclaimed king after his victory.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=87}}{{sfn|Bartl|<U+010C>i<U+010D>aj|Koh<U+00FA>tova|Letz|2002|p=27}}

Solomon sent his envoys to Henry IV and promised "six of the strongest fortified cities in Hungary" if his brother-in-law would help him to depose G<U+00E9>za.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=99}} He was even ready to accept the German monarch's suzerainty.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=87}}

Henry IV invaded Hungary in August.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=99}} He marched as far as [[V<U+00E1>c]], but soon withdrew from Hungary without defeating G<U+00E9>za.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=32}} Nevertheless, the German invasion strengthened Solomon's rule in the region of his two fortresses,{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=99}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=32}} where he continued to exercise all royal prerogatives, including coinage.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=94}} His mother and wife left him and followed Henry IV to Germany.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=94}}

{{Quote|''That summer'' [Henry IV] ''undertook an expedition into Hungary to help King Salomon, who also because of his insolent and shameful crimes had been deposed from his office by his father's brother'' (sic) ''and the other magnates of the kingdom, for whose counsels he cared little.'' [Henry IV]'', however, was able to achieve nothing of what he wished there, namely to restore Salomon. Finally, bringing back his sister, Queen Judith, the wife of Salomon, he returned home to [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]&nbsp;...''|[[Berthold of Reichenau]]: ''Chronicle (Second Version)''<ref>''Berthold of Reichenau, Chronicle (Second Version)'' (year 1074), p. 131.</ref>}}
[[File:Denar of Solomon.jpg|thumb |left |190px |alt=Solomon's denar |Solomon's denar]]
Solomon attempted to convince [[Pope Gregory VII]] to support him against G<U+00E9>za.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=88}} However, the pope condemned him for having accepted his kingdom "as a fief from the king of the Germans"<ref>''Pope Gregory VII's letter to King Solomon of Hungary, claiming suzerainty over that kingdom'', p. 48.</ref> and claimed suzerainty over Hungary.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|pp=88-89}} Thereafter it was Henry IV's support which enabled Solomon to resist G<U+00E9>za's all attempts at taking Moson and Pressburg.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}} The German monarch even sent one of his main opponents, Bishop [[Burchard II (Bishop of Halberstadt)|Burchard II of Halberstadt]] into exile to Solomon in June 1076.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=152}} Solomon's wife, Queen Judith, who was about to return to her husband, undertook to take the imprisoned bishop to Hungary, but the prelate managed to escape.{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=152}}

G<U+00E9>za decided to start new negotiations with Solomon.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|pp=90-91}} However, he died on 25 April 1077 and his partisans proclaimed his brother, Ladislaus, king.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=92}} The new king occupied Moson in 1079, thus Solomon could preserve only Pressburg.{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=92}} In 1080{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=92}} or 1081,{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}} the two cousins concluded a treaty, according to which Solomon acknowledged Ladislaus as king in exchange for "revenues sufficient to bear the expenses of a king".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 94.133), p. 128.</ref>{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=93}}

==Later life==

Solomon did not give up his ambitions even after his abdication. He was arrested for plotting against his cousin,{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=93}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}} then held in captivity in [[Visegr<U+00E1>d]].{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=93}} He was released "on the occasion of the canonization of [[Stephen I of Hungary|King St. Stephen]] and the [[Saint Emeric of Hungary|blessed Emeric the confessor]]"<ref name="Chronicon_95.134_128">''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 95.134), p. 128.</ref> around 17 August 1083.{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}}{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=92}} According to [[Hartvik]]'s ''Legend of King Saint Stephen'', King Ladislaus ordered Solomon's release, because nobody could open the grave of the saintly king until Solomon was held in captivity.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=94}}

Having been liberated, Solomon first visited his wife in [[Regensburg]], "although she was not grateful for this",<ref>''Bernold of St Blasien, Chronicle'' (year 1084), p. 273.</ref> according to the nearly contemporaneous [[Bernold of St Blasien]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}} From Germany, Solomon fled to the "Cumans"{{mdash}}in fact Pechenegs, according to the historians Gyula Krist<U+00F3> and P<U+00E1>l Engel{{mdash}}who were dwelling in the regions east of the [[Carpathian Mountains]] and north of the [[Lower Danube]].{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}}{{sfn|Engel|2001|p=33}} Solomon promised one of their chiefs, Kutesk, that "he would give him the right of possession over the province of Transylvania and would take his daughter as wife"<ref name="Chronicon_95.134_128"/> if Kutesk and his people would help him to regain his throne.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}}{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=94}} They invaded the regions along the Upper Tisza "with a great multitude"<ref name="Chronicon_95.134_128"/> of the "Cumans", but King Ladislaus routed and forced them to withdraw from Hungary.{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=94}}{{sfn|<U+00C9>rszegi|Solymosi|1981|p=93}}

At the head of "a large contingent of Dacians"<ref>''Anna Comnena: The Alexiad'' (7.1.), p. 217.</ref> (Hungarians), Solomon joined a huge army of Cumans and Pechenegs who invaded the Byzantine Empire in 1087.{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=300}} The Byzantines routed the invaders in the mountains of [[Bulgaria (theme)|Bulgaria]].{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=300}} Solomon seems to have died fighting in the battlefield, because Bernold of St. Blasien narrates that he "died courageously after an incredible slaughter of the enemy after he bravely undertook an enterprise against the King of the Greeks" in 1087.<ref>''Bernold of St Blasien, Chronicle'' (year 1087), p. 290.</ref>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=95-96}}

Reports of later sources prove that Solomon became the subject of popular legends.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=148}} For instance, the ''Illuminated Chronicle'' writes that Solomon "repented of his sins, so far as human understanding may reach" after the battle, and passed the last years of his life "in pilgrimage and prayer, in fastings and watchings, in labour and contrition".<ref>''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 96.136), p. 129.</ref>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|pp=95-96}}{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=148}} According to these sources, Solomon died in [[Pula]] on the [[Istrian Peninsula]]{{sfn|Kosztolnyik|1981|p=94}} where he was venerated as a saint.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=97}} However, he was never officially canonized.{{sfn|Klaniczay|2002|p=148}} His alleged tombstone is now in a local museum.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=97}}

{{Quote|[Solomon] ''was now completely at a loss, and after returning to his queen at [[Admont Abbey|Admont]] he spent a few days with her before returning to [[Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r]] in monk's habit. There, the story goes, his brother'' (sic) ''Ladislas was distributing alms to the poor with his own hands on the porch of the church of the Blessed Virgin, and Solomon was among the recipients. When Ladislas looked closely he realised who it was. After the distribution was over Ladislas made careful inquiries. He intended Solomon no harm, but Solomon assumed he did, and quit Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r, making for the [[Adriatic Sea|Adriatic]]. There he passed the rest of his days in complete poverty in a city named Pula; he died in destitution and was buried there, never having returned to his wife. ''|[[Simon of K<U+00E9>za]]: ''[[Gesta Hunnorum et Hungarorum|The Deeds of the Hungarians]]''<ref>''Simon of K<U+00E9>za: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 2.61), pp.&nbsp;135<U+2013>137.</ref>}}

