{{ahnentafel bottom}}

Solomon's wife, [[Judith of Swabia|Judith]], who was born in 1048, was the third daughter of [[Henry III, Holy Roman Emperor]] and his second wife, [[Agnes de Poitou]].{{sfn|Robinson|1999|p=19}} Their wedding took place in Sz<U+00E9>kesfeh<U+00E9>rv<U+00E1>r in June 1063.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=87}} The marriage remained childless.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=96}} They first separated from each other around 1075.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=94}} According to Bernold of St Blasien, neither Solomon nor his wife had "kept the marriage contract: on the contrary, they had not been afraid, in opposition to the [[Paul the Apostle|apostle]], to [[First Epistle to the Corinthians|defraud each other]]."<ref>''Bernold of St Blasien, Chronicle'' (year 1084), p. 274.</ref>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=95}} Having been informed on Solomon's death, Judith married Duke [[W<U+0142>adys<U+0142>aw I Herman]] of Poland in 1088.{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=96}} In contrast with all contemporaneous sources, the late 13th-century Simon of K<U+00E9>za writes that Judith "spurned all suitors" after her husband's death, although "many princes in Germany sought her hand".<ref>''Simon of K<U+00E9>za: The Deeds of the Hungarians'' (ch. 2.61), p. 137.</ref>{{sfn|Krist<U+00F3>|Makk|1996|p=96}}

